{"title_page": "T. P. Gill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2014}}\n'''Thomas Patrick (T. P.) Gill''' (25 Oct 1858 \u2013 19 January 1931) was a prominent member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] in the late 19th and early 20th century and a [[Member of Parliament]] in the British House of Commons representing the [[South Louth (UK Parliament constituency)|South Louth]] constituency unopposed from 1885 to 1892. His uncle Peter was an unsuccessful election candidate in 1868 in [[County Tipperary]].\n\nGill was born 25th October 1858, in Ballygraigue, [[Nenagh]], Co. Tipperary, the eldest son of Robert Gill, a civil engineer.<ref name=\"TIWW\">{{cite TIWW |article= Gill, Thomas Patrick|page=91 }}</ref>  He was educated at [[Trinity College Dublin]] and became a journalist, firstly as editor of the Catholic World magazine of New York, and an associate editor of the North American Review, 1883\u201385.  He married in 1882 to Annie Fennell of Dublin, they had three children.\n\nGill was a friend and political ally of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]]. After the death of Parnell he remained with the Irish Parliamentary Party. He worked with [[Horace Plunkett]] in developing the Irish co-operative movement. He was member and honorary secretary to the 1895 Recess Committee which led to the formation of both the Department of Agriculture and Technical Instruction (DATI), forerunner of the Irish Department of Agriculture, and the Vocational Education Committees (VEC).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/publicat/annualrep/AReport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060203180104/http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/publicat/annualrep/AReport.pdf |archivedate=3 February 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gill's key work for the Recess committee was research into the state aid to agriculture in France and Denmark.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/14342 ''Ireland in the New Century''], Chapt.8</ref> In February 1900, he was appointed Secretary of the new Department of Agriculture and Technical Instruction in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=|day_of_week=Saturday |date=3 February 1900 |page_number=13 |issue=36056}}</ref> In 1907, Gill was appointed Chairman of the Departmental Committee on Irish Forestry.  He also served on a number of governmental committees concerning agriculture and agricultural production  He was President of the Irish Technical Instruction Association from 1925 to 1929.<ref>Who's Who, House of Commons, London</ref><ref name=\"TIWW\" />\n\nGill was an uncle of former [[Workers' Party of Ireland|Workers' Party]] president and [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] TD [[Tom\u00e1s Mac Giolla]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-thomas-gill|T. P. Gill}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of parliament]] for [[South Louth (UK Parliament constituency)|South Louth]]\n       |years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Daniel Ambrose]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gill, T. P.}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Louth constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:People from Nenagh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2014}}\n'''Thomas Patrick (T. P.) Gill''' (25 Oct 1858 \u2013 19 January 1931) was a prominent member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] in the late 19th and early 20th century and a [[Member of Parliament]] in the British House of Commons representing the [[South Louth (UK Parliament constituency)|South Louth]] constituency unopposed from 1885 to 1892. His uncle Peter was an unsuccessful election candidate in 1868 in [[County Tipperary]].\n\nGill was born 25th October 1858, in Ballygraigue, [[Nenagh]], Co. Tipperary, the eldest son of Robert Gill, a civil engineer.<ref name=\"TIWW\">{{cite TIWW |article= Gill, Thomas Patrick|page=91 }}</ref>  He was educated at [[Trinity College Dublin]] and became a journalist, firstly as editor of the Catholic World magazine of New York, and an associate editor of the North American Review, 1883-85.  He married in 1882 to Annie Fennell of Dublin, they had three children.\n\nGill was a friend and political ally of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]]. After the death of Parnell he remained with the Irish Parliamentary Party. He worked with [[Horace Plunkett]] in developing the Irish co-operative movement. He was member and honorary secretary to the 1895 Recess Committee which led to the formation of both the Department of Agriculture and Technical Instruction (DATI), forerunner of the Irish Department of Agriculture, and the Vocational Education Committees (VEC).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/publicat/annualrep/AReport.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060203180104/http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/publicat/annualrep/AReport.pdf |archivedate=3 February 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Gill's key work for the Recess committee was research into the state aid to agriculture in France and Denmark.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/14342 ''Ireland in the New Century''], Chapt.8</ref> In February 1900, he was appointed Secretary of the new Department of Agriculture and Technical Instruction in Ireland.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=|day_of_week=Saturday |date=3 February 1900 |page_number=13 |issue=36056}}</ref> In 1907, Gill was appointed Chairman of the Departmental Committee on Irish Forestry.  He also served on a number of governmental committees concerning agriculture and agricultural production  He was President of the Irish Technical Instruction Association from 1925 to 1929.<ref>Who's Who, House of Commons, London</ref><ref name=\"TIWW\" />\n\nGill was an uncle of former [[Workers' Party of Ireland|Workers' Party]] president and [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] TD [[Tom\u00e1s Mac Giolla]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-thomas-gill|T. P. Gill}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of parliament]] for [[South Louth (UK Parliament constituency)|South Louth]]\n       |years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Daniel Ambrose]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gill, T. P.}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Louth constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:People from Nenagh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1883-85 \u2192 1883\u201385", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T._P._Gill"}
{"title_page": "James Gilhooly", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:All-for-Ireland League MPs, 1910.jpg|thumb|350px|right|[[All-for-Ireland League]] group portrait of five of its Independent [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|Members of Parliament]], in the \"[[Cork Free Press]]\" July 30th 1910. <br>These are: [[Patrick Guiney]] ([[North Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|North Cork]]), '''James Gilhooly''' ([[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]), [[Maurice Healy]] ([[North-East Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|North-east Cork]]), [[D. D. Sheehan]] ([[Mid Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Cork]]), and [[Eugene Crean]] ([[South-East Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|South-east Cork]]).]]\n\n'''James Gilhooly''' (1847\u20131916) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] politician and [[Member of Parliament|MP.]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] as member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]], from 1910 the [[All-for-Ireland League|All-for Ireland Party]], who represented his constituency ([[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]) from 1885 for 30 years until his death, retaining his seat in eight elections (four of them contested).\n\nEducated privately, he was the son of a coastguard officer and as a  draper and storekeeper by trade, he established an extensive grocery business in [[Bantry]]. He married Mary Collins in 1882.\n\nIn 1867, the authorities believed him to be a Fenian \"Head Centre\" in the Bantry area. During the [[Land League]]'s [[Land War]] and the later [[Plan of Campaign]] in the late 1880s he was imprisoned several times under the [[Irish Coercion Bill|Coercion Act]], which permitted imprisonment without trial, and served a three-month sentence for his role in the ''No Rent Manifesto'' of 1881. He was first elected to parliament in the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] as a member of the Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP).\n\nAs chair person of the local branch of the [[United Irish League]] he was some-time president of the local [[Irish National League]].  Involved in local politics, he served as Chairman of the Bantry town commissioners and at various times chairman of the Bantry [[Rural District Council]] and was a member of the [[Cork County Council]] as an ''ex officio'' member of the Bantry RDC from its establishment in 1899.\n\nAfter the \"Split\" in the IPP over Parnell's leadership he joined the anti-Parnellite [[Irish National Federation]] majority group, then joined the re-united Irish Party again in 1900, for which he was elected in the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]]. He was however one of [[William O'Brien]]'s closest political supporters, joining his secession from the IPP in 1903, then elected in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910 general election]] as a member of O'Briens's [[All-for-Ireland League|All-for-Ireland Party]] (AFIL), of which he was Chairman.\n\nHe died on 16 October 1916  at Madame Goulding's Private Hospital, Patrick's Place, Cork and was buried at Abbey Cemetery, Bantry, the town closing down for his funeral and many houses showed black crepe.\n\nThe ensuing bitter West-Cork by-election has a place in history as the first after the Rising and the last in which the Irish Party narrowly captured a seat and as the self-induced demise of the AFIL. At stake in the bitterly fought by-election was not just one of the 103 seats in the House of Commons. The great issue was William O\u2019Brien's AFIL versus John Redmond's Irish Party. In November three candidates were nominated, the third also a local AFIL supporter and member who stood in protest after O\u2019Brien had passed him over in favour of a [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] close candidate (Frank Healy), thereby splitting the AFIL vote to the detriment of O\u2019Brien's party.<ref>A bitter by-election in 1916: West Cork pivotal point in transition to new era; ''Southern Star Centenary  Edition \u2013 1889\u20131989''<br /> Article pp 89\u201390 by George D. Kelleher, Inniscarra, co. Cork</ref> (At that time seats were won by \"candidates first past the post\", or uncontested as in 1918 by [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] of Sinn F\u00e9in)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Who's Who in British Members of Parliament 1886-1918'', Michael Stenton and Stephen Lees, p.&nbsp;136\n* ''Who Was Who 1916\u20131928'', Adam and Charles Black, London (1929),  p.&nbsp;407\n* ''Who's Who in The long gestation'', Patrick Maume (1999),  p.&nbsp;229\n* ''A Biographical Dictionary of Cork'', Tim Cadogan & Jeremiah Falvey (2006)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-james-gilhooly/index.html Hansard: Speeches of James Gilhooly in House of Commons]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]\n |years=[[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)#1916|1916]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Daniel O'Leary (Irish nationalist politician)|Daniel O'Leary]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilhooley, James}}\n[[Category:1847 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish land reform activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Anti-Parnellite MPs]]\n[[Category:All-for-Ireland League MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Cork]]\n[[Category:People from Bantry]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:All-for-Ireland League MPs, 1910.jpg|thumb|350px|right|[[All-for-Ireland League]] group portrait of five of its Independent [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|Members of Parliament]], in the \"[[Cork Free Press]]\" July 30th 1910. <br>These are: [[Patrick Guiney]] ([[North Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|North Cork]]), '''James Gilhooly''' ([[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]), [[Maurice Healy]] ([[North-East Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|North-east Cork]]), [[D. D. Sheehan]] ([[Mid Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Cork]]), and [[Eugene Crean]] ([[South-East Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|South-east Cork]]).]]\n\n'''James Gilhooly''' (1847\u20131916) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] politician and [[Member of Parliament|MP.]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] as member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]], from 1910 the [[All-for-Ireland League|All-for Ireland Party]], who represented his constituency ([[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]) from 1885 for 30 years until his death, retaining his seat in eight elections (four of them contested).\n\nEducated privately, he was the son of a coastguard officer and as a  draper and storekeeper by trade, he established an extensive grocery business in [[Bantry]]. He married Mary Collins in 1882.\n\nIn 1867, the authorities believed him to be a Fenian \"Head Centre\" in the Bantry area. During the [[Land League]]'s [[Land War]] and the later [[Plan of Campaign]] in the late 1880s he was imprisoned several times under the [[Irish Coercion Bill|Coercion Act]], which permitted imprisonment without trial, and served a three-month sentence for his role in the ''No Rent Manifesto'' of 1881. He was first elected to parliament in the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] as a member of the Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP).\n\nAs chair person of the local branch of the [[United Irish League]] he was some-time president of the local [[Irish National League]].  Involved in local politics, he served as Chairman of the Bantry town commissioners and at various times chairman of the Bantry [[Rural District Council]] and was a member of the [[Cork County Council]] as an ''ex officio'' member of the Bantry RDC from its establishment in 1899.\n\nAfter the \"Split\" in the IPP over Parnell's leadership he joined the anti-Parnellite [[Irish National Federation]] majority group, then joined the re-united Irish Party again in 1900, for which he was elected in the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]]. He was however one of [[William O'Brien]]'s closest political supporters, joining his secession from the IPP in 1903, then elected in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|1910 general election]] as a member of O'Briens's [[All-for-Ireland League|All-for-Ireland Party]] (AFIL), of which he was Chairman.\n\nHe died on 16 October 1916  at Madame Goulding\u2019s Private Hospital, Patrick\u2019s Place, Cork and was buried at Abbey Cemetery, Bantry, the town closing down for his funeral and many houses showed black crepe.\n\nThe ensuing bitter West-Cork by-election has a place in history as the first after the Rising and the last in which the Irish Party narrowly captured a seat and as the self-induced demise of the AFIL. At stake in the bitterly fought by-election was not just one of the 103 seats in the House of Commons. The great issue was William O\u2019Brien\u2019s AFIL versus John Redmond\u2019s Irish Party. In November three candidates were nominated, the third also a local AFIL supporter and member who stood in protest after O\u2019Brien had passed him over in favour of a [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] close candidate (Frank Healy), thereby splitting the AFIL vote to the detriment of O\u2019Brien\u2019s party.<ref>A bitter by-election in 1916: West Cork pivotal point in transition to new era; ''Southern Star Centenary  Edition \u2013 1889\u20131989''<br /> Article pp 89\u201390 by George D. Kelleher, Inniscarra, co. Cork</ref> (At that time seats were won by \"candidates first past the post\", or uncontested as in 1918 by [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]] of Sinn F\u00e9in)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Who's Who in British Members of Parliament 1886-1918'', Michael Stenton and Stephen Lees, p.&nbsp;136\n* ''Who Was Who 1916\u20131928'', Adam and Charles Black, London (1929),  p.&nbsp;407\n* ''Who's Who in The long gestation'', Patrick Maume (1999),  p.&nbsp;229\n* ''A Biographical Dictionary of Cork'', Tim Cadogan & Jeremiah Falvey (2006)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-james-gilhooly/index.html Hansard: Speeches of James Gilhooly in House of Commons]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cork]]\n |years=[[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[West Cork (UK Parliament constituency)#1916|1916]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Daniel O'Leary (Irish nationalist politician)|Daniel O'Leary]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilhooley, James}}\n[[Category:1847 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish land reform activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Anti-Parnellite MPs]]\n[[Category:All-for-Ireland League MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Cork]]\n[[Category:People from Bantry]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gilhooly"}
{"title_page": "Savile Crossley, 1st Baron Somerleyton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Somerleyton\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCVO|PC}}\n| image = Savile Brinton Crossley, Vanity Fair, 1888-11-17.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \"Lowestoft\". Caricature by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1888.\n| order1 = [[Paymaster General]]\n| term_start1 = 11 March 1902 \n| term_end1 = 4 December 1905\n| monarch1 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Arthur Balfour]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Charles Spencer-Churchill, 9th Duke of Marlborough|The Duke of Marlborough]]\n| successor1 = [[Richard Causton, 1st Baron Southwark|Richard Causton]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|14 June 1857|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|25 February 1935|14 June 1857}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionist]]  \n| alma_mater =  \n| spouse = Phyllis de Bathe <br>(1869-1948) \n}}\n\n'''Savile Brinton Crossley, 1st Baron Somerleyton''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|GCVO|PC}} (14 June 1857 \u2013 25 February 1935), known as '''Sir Savile Crossley, Bt''', from 1872 to 1916, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionist]] politician who served as [[Paymaster General]] from 1902 to 1905.\n\n==Background==\nCrossley was the only son of the businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician [[Sir Francis Crossley, 1st Baronet]], and his wife Martha Eliza, daughter of Henry Brinton.<ref name=\"Debrett's\">Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCrossley was elected to parliament for [[Lowestoft (UK Parliament constituency)|Lowestoft]] in 1885, as a Liberal. In 1886 he joined the Liberal Unionists and held the seat until 1892 when he chose not to stand again for Lowestoft.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons4.htm leighrayment.com House of Commons: London University to Lymington]</ref> \n[[File:Sir Savile B. Crossley - Suffolk Celebrities 1893.jpg|thumb|left|Pictured in ''Suffolk Celebrities'', 1893]]\nIn 1897 Crossley stood as a Liberal Unionist in a by-election for [[Halifax (UK Parliament constituency)|Halifax]]. He failed that time but stood again in Halifax in the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]] and won the seat.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Hcommons1.htm leighrayment.com House of Commons: Hackney to Harwich]</ref> He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Suffolk]] for 1896\u201397.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26720|page=1596|date=10 March 1896}}</ref>\n\nCrossley was involved in work regarding the National Coronation gift from the people to their new monarch King [[Edward VII]], and was present as it was awarded to the King two days after the [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|coronation]], on 11 August 1902. For his service, he was invested as a Member (fourth class) of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (MVO).<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=12 August 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36844| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27467 |page=5461 |date=22 August 1902}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1902 he was appointed [[Paymaster General]]<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/peers/peersS4.htm leighrayment.com Peerage: Slim to Stamfordham]</ref> in the [[Conservative Government 1895-1905|Conservative government]] of [[Arthur Balfour]] and was admitted to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] in December of the same year.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27504 |date=16 December 1902 |page=8663 }}</ref> He remained in this post until the government fell in December 1905, and he lost his seat in the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] that followed shortly after. Crossley was never to re-enter the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]].\n\nHowever, in 1916 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Somerleyton''', of [[Somerleyton]] in the County of [[Suffolk]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29651 |date=4 July 1916 |page=6597 }}</ref> Two years later he was appointed a [[Lord-in-waiting]] (government whip) in the [[Coalition Government 1916-1922|coalition government]] of [[David Lloyd George]]. The coalition fell in 1922, but Somerleyton remained as a whip also in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] administrations of [[Bonar Law]] and [[Stanley Baldwin]]. However, after the first Baldwin government fell in 1924, he was never to hold ministerial office again.\n\n==Military and civic appointments==\nCrossley held the appointment of honorary [[Major (British Army and Royal Marines)|major]] in the Army. He was on 2 April 1893 appointed a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in [[Norfolk Artillery Militia|The Prince of Wales's Own Norfolk Artillery]], a [[Militia (United Kingdom)|Militia]] Battalion stationed at [[Great Yarmouth]] in [[Norfolk]].<ref>Hart\u2032s Army list, 1901</ref> He volunteered for active service in [[South Africa]] during the [[Second Boer War]], and was on 10 March 1900 appointed captain in the [[Imperial Yeomanry]] and attached to its 18th battalion.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27172 |page=1630 |date=9 March 1900}}</ref> In early May 1902 he was back as a captain in the Norfolk Artillery.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27431 |page=3016 |date=6 May 1902}}</ref> He was promoted to the substantive rank of major and honorary lieutenant-colonel of the battalion later the same month,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27471 |page=3462 |date=27 May 1902}}</ref> and later served as lieutenant-colonel commanding the Battalion.\n\n==Family==\nLord Somerleyton married Phyllis de Bathe, daughter of General [[Sir Henry Percival de Bathe, 4th Baronet|Sir Henry Percival de Bathe]], in 1887. He died in February 1935, aged 77, and was succeeded in the baronetcy and barony by his eldest son, Francis Savile Crossley. His younger son, John, was the father of [[Belinda Douglas-Scott-Montagu, Baroness Montagu of Beaulieu]]. Lady Somerleyton died in 1948.<ref name=\"Debrett's\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-savile-crossley | Sir Savile Crossley }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lowestoft (UK Parliament constituency)|Lowestoft]]\n | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Harry Foster (politician)|Harry Foster]] }}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Halifax (UK Parliament constituency)|Halifax]]\n | years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] \u2013 [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\n | with   = [[John Henry Whitley]]\n | before = [[Alfred Billson]] <br />[[Alfred Arnold|Sir Alfred Arnold]]\n | after  = [[John Henry Whitley]]<br />[[James Parker (Labour politician)|James Parker]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Paymaster General]] | before=[[Charles Spencer-Churchill, 9th Duke of Marlborough|The Duke of Marlborough]] | after=[[Richard Causton, 1st Baron Southwark|Richard Causton]] | years=1902\u20131905}}\n\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] \n | with = [[Richard Herschell, 2nd Baron Herschell|The Lord Herschell]] 1918\u20131919 <br /> [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 2nd Baron Stanmore|The Lord Stanmore]] 1918\u20131922<br /> [[John Brocklehurst, 1st Baron Ranksborough|The Lord Ranksborough]] 1918\u20131921<br /> [[Arthur Annesley, 11th Viscount Valentia|The Viscount Valentia]] 1918\u20131924 <br /> [[George Child Villiers, 8th Earl of Jersey|The Earl of Jersey]] 1919 <br /> [[Orlando Bridgeman, 5th Earl of Bradford|The Earl of Bradford]] 1919\u20131924 <br /> [[Richard Onslow, 5th Earl of Onslow|The Earl of Onslow]] 1919\u20131920<br /> [[George Bingham, 5th Earl of Lucan|The Earl of Lucan]] 1920\u20131924<br /> [[George Villiers, 6th Earl of Clarendon|The Earl of Clarendon]] 1921\u20131922 <br /> [[James Harris, 5th Earl of Malmesbury|The Earl of Malmesbury]] 1922\u20131924 <br /> [[Arnold Keppel, 8th Earl of Albemarle|The Earl of Albemarle]] 1922\u20131924  | before= [[Richard Herschell, 2nd Baron Herschell|The Lord Herschell]] <br /> [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 2nd Baron Stanmore|The Lord Stanmore]]  <br /> [[John Brocklehurst, 1st Baron Ranksborough|The Lord Ranksborough]] <br /> [[Arthur Annesley, 11th Viscount Valentia|The Viscount Valentia]] <br /> [[Hylton Jolliffe, 3rd Baron Hylton|The Lord Hylton]] | after= [[Herbrand Sackville, 9th Earl De La Warr|The Earl De La Warr]] <br /> [[Kenneth Muir Mackenzie, 1st Baron Muir-Mackenzie|The Lord Muir-Mackenzie]]  | years=1918\u20131924}}\n\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Somerleyton]] | before=New creation | after= [[Francis Crossley, 2nd Baron Somerleyton|Francis Savile Crossley]] | years=1916\u20131935 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Paymaster General}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somerleyton, Savile Crossley, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) Baronesses- and Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Liberal Unionist Party MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886|Crossley, Savile]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892|Crossley, Savile]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906|Crossley, Savile]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Liberal Unionist Party peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Somerleyton\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCVO|PC}}\n| image = Savile Brinton Crossley, Vanity Fair, 1888-11-17.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \"Lowestoft\". Caricature by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1888.\n| order1 = [[Paymaster General]]\n| term_start1 = 11 March 1902 \n| term_end1 = 4 December 1905\n| monarch1 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Arthur Balfour]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Charles Spencer-Churchill, 9th Duke of Marlborough|The Duke of Marlborough]]\n| successor1 = [[Richard Causton, 1st Baron Southwark|Richard Causton]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|14 June 1857|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|25 February 1935|14 June 1857}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionist]]  \n| alma_mater =  \n| spouse = Phyllis de Bathe <br>(1869-1948) \n}}\n\n'''Savile Brinton Crossley, 1st Baron Somerleyton''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|GCVO|PC}} (14 June 1857 \u2013 25 February 1935), known as '''Sir Savile Crossley, Bt''', from 1872 to 1916, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionist]] politician who served as [[Paymaster General]] from 1902 to 1905.\n\n==Background==\nCrossley was the only son of the businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician [[Sir Francis Crossley, 1st Baronet]], and his wife Martha Eliza, daughter of Henry Brinton.<ref name=\"Debrett's\">Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCrossley was elected to parliament for [[Lowestoft (UK Parliament constituency)|Lowestoft]] in 1885, as a Liberal. In 1886 he joined the Liberal Unionists and held the seat until 1892 when he chose not to stand again for Lowestoft.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons4.htm leighrayment.com House of Commons: London University to Lymington]</ref> \n[[File:Sir Savile B. Crossley - Suffolk Celebrities 1893.jpg|thumb|left|Pictured in ''Suffolk Celebrities'', 1893]]\nIn 1897 Crossley stood as a Liberal Unionist in a by-election for [[Halifax (UK Parliament constituency)|Halifax]]. He failed that time but stood again in Halifax in the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]] and won the seat.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Hcommons1.htm leighrayment.com House of Commons: Hackney to Harwich]</ref> He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Suffolk]] for 1896-97.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=26720|page=1596|date=10 March 1896}}</ref>\n\nCrossley was involved in work regarding the National Coronation gift from the people to their new monarch King [[Edward VII]], and was present as it was awarded to the King two days after the [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|coronation]], on 11 August 1902. For his service, he was invested as a Member (fourth class) of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (MVO).<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=12 August 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36844| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27467 |page=5461 |date=22 August 1902}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1902 he was appointed [[Paymaster General]]<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/peers/peersS4.htm leighrayment.com Peerage: Slim to Stamfordham]</ref> in the [[Conservative Government 1895-1905|Conservative government]] of [[Arthur Balfour]] and was admitted to the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] in December of the same year.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27504 |date=16 December 1902 |page=8663 }}</ref> He remained in this post until the government fell in December 1905, and he lost his seat in the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]] that followed shortly after. Crossley was never to re-enter the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]].\n\nHowever, in 1916 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Somerleyton''', of [[Somerleyton]] in the County of [[Suffolk]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29651 |date=4 July 1916 |page=6597 }}</ref> Two years later he was appointed a [[Lord-in-waiting]] (government whip) in the [[Coalition Government 1916-1922|coalition government]] of [[David Lloyd George]]. The coalition fell in 1922, but Somerleyton remained as a whip also in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] administrations of [[Bonar Law]] and [[Stanley Baldwin]]. However, after the first Baldwin government fell in 1924, he was never to hold ministerial office again.\n\n==Military and civic appointments==\nCrossley held the appointment of honorary [[Major (British Army and Royal Marines)|major]] in the Army. He was on 2 April 1893 appointed a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in [[Norfolk Artillery Militia|The Prince of Wales's Own Norfolk Artillery]], a [[Militia (United Kingdom)|Militia]] Battalion stationed at [[Great Yarmouth]] in [[Norfolk]].<ref>Hart\u2032s Army list, 1901</ref> He volunteered for active service in [[South Africa]] during the [[Second Boer War]], and was on 10 March 1900 appointed captain in the [[Imperial Yeomanry]] and attached to its 18th battalion.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27172 |page=1630 |date=9 March 1900}}</ref> In early May 1902 he was back as a captain in the Norfolk Artillery.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27431 |page=3016 |date=6 May 1902}}</ref> He was promoted to the substantive rank of major and honorary lieutenant-colonel of the battalion later the same month,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27471 |page=3462 |date=27 May 1902}}</ref> and later served as lieutenant-colonel commanding the Battalion.\n\n==Family==\nLord Somerleyton married Phyllis de Bathe, daughter of General [[Sir Henry Percival de Bathe, 4th Baronet|Sir Henry Percival de Bathe]], in 1887. He died in February 1935, aged 77, and was succeeded in the baronetcy and barony by his eldest son, Francis Savile Crossley. His younger son, John, was the father of [[Belinda Douglas-Scott-Montagu, Baroness Montagu of Beaulieu]]. Lady Somerleyton died in 1948.<ref name=\"Debrett's\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-savile-crossley | Sir Savile Crossley }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lowestoft (UK Parliament constituency)|Lowestoft]]\n | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Harry Foster (politician)|Harry Foster]] }}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Halifax (UK Parliament constituency)|Halifax]]\n | years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] \u2013 [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\n | with   = [[John Henry Whitley]]\n | before = [[Alfred Billson]] <br />[[Alfred Arnold|Sir Alfred Arnold]]\n | after  = [[John Henry Whitley]]<br />[[James Parker (Labour politician)|James Parker]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Paymaster General]] | before=[[Charles Spencer-Churchill, 9th Duke of Marlborough|The Duke of Marlborough]] | after=[[Richard Causton, 1st Baron Southwark|Richard Causton]] | years=1902\u20131905}}\n\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] \n | with = [[Richard Herschell, 2nd Baron Herschell|The Lord Herschell]] 1918\u20131919 <br /> [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 2nd Baron Stanmore|The Lord Stanmore]] 1918\u20131922<br /> [[John Brocklehurst, 1st Baron Ranksborough|Th